explanation.detail:
• Explanation :
• Medulla at the level of sensory decussation - Hypoglossal nucleus: Responsible for controlling the muscles of the tongue , is located in the medulla .
• Midbrain at level of inferior colliculus - Decussation of superior cerebellar peduncle: The decussation of the superior cerebellar peduncle occurs at the level of the inferior colliculus in the midbrain .
• Tegmentum of upper pons - Motor nucleus of trigeminal nerve: Which controls the muscles of mastication, is indeed located in the pons, specifically in its tegmentum .
• Medulla at level of motor decussation - Cuneate and Gracilias nucleus: These nuclei are most dorsal and caudal in medulla at the level of pyramidal decussation . The dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway synapse into second order neurons from their perspective dorsal root ganglia neurons at these nuclei.
• Midbrain at level of superior colliculus - Edinger westphal nucleus: It is associated with the oculomotor nerve and controls the pupillary reflex and lens shape , is located in the midbrain, near the level of the superior colliculus.
• Tegmentum of lower pons - Facial colliculus: The facial colliculus, which is not actually a nucleus but a surface feature on the floor of the fourth ventricle created by the facial nerve fibers wrapping around the abducens nucleus , is located in the pons.
• Educational Objective:
• Each brainstem division is associated with specific nuclei or structures:
• The hypoglossal nucleus in the medulla controls tongue muscles ;
• The decussation of the superior cerebellar peduncle occurs in the midbrain at the level of the inferior colliculus ;
• The motor nucleus of the trigeminal nerve, controlling mastication muscles , is in the tegmentum of the upper pons ;
• The cuneate and gracile nuclei, involved in the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway , are in the medulla at the level of motor decussation;
• The Edinger-Westphal nucleus, linked to the oculomotor nerve for pupillary reflex and lens shape , is near the superior colliculus in the midbrain;
• The facial colliculus, a structure created by facial nerve fibers around the abducens nucleus , is in the tegmentum of the lower pons.
